WEBVTT

00:01.260 --> 00:03.430
That is rad.
I gotta show the guys.

00:03.430 --> 00:06.100
When we get big boxes,
we always get excited

00:06.100 --> 00:07.370
'cause it's usually
really cool stuff.

00:07.370 --> 00:08.940
-What did we get?
-Nice.

00:08.940 --> 00:10.300
-From hot wheels.
-Oh, look at that!

00:10.310 --> 00:11.710
How rad is that?

00:11.710 --> 00:14.040
Christie: We just got
the red line club,

00:14.040 --> 00:16.780
hi-po hauler hot wheels
in the big box today.

00:16.780 --> 00:17.980
It's amazing.

00:17.980 --> 00:19.850
They did a great job
putting all the details

00:19.850 --> 00:21.180
that were on our truck.
-Right.

00:21.180 --> 00:22.650
Yeah, and the way you can
see through the back

00:22.650 --> 00:23.920
and the bed and everything.

00:23.920 --> 00:26.720
You guys did a really
good job. I'm super proud.

00:26.720 --> 00:29.960
We are super, super excited
that hot wheels

00:29.960 --> 00:33.360
made a toy out of a car
that we did.

00:33.360 --> 00:36.400
In my opinion, we rock.

00:36.400 --> 00:37.530
When ours get here
just let us know.

00:37.530 --> 00:39.600
Yeah, I'll get right on that.

00:39.600 --> 00:42.300
[ engine revs, tires peal ]
[ laughs ] whoo!

00:42.300 --> 00:44.270
Narrator: Right now on
"fast n' loud"...

00:44.270 --> 00:48.310
Hot rod hunter richard rawlings
and his band of monkeys...

00:48.310 --> 00:52.150
-Yeah.
-...Are breaking all the rules

00:52.150 --> 00:55.050
as they try to transform
an old buick riviera...

00:55.050 --> 00:57.350
I'm concerned this is the size
of two corvettes.

00:57.350 --> 01:00.420
...Into gas monkey's first ever
sema super-build.

01:00.420 --> 01:02.720
I want this thing
to be rippin' it.

01:02.730 --> 01:04.630
Narrator: And then...

01:04.630 --> 01:07.030
You probably didn't even
know this, but I have a stepson.

01:07.030 --> 01:09.360
...Richard grows
the gas monkey family.

01:09.370 --> 01:11.430
What the [bleep]?
A stepson?

01:11.430 --> 01:14.540
...Before sending them
on a cross-country mission...

01:14.540 --> 01:16.200
Where are we eating, boys?

01:16.210 --> 01:19.640
...To bring home an indy legend
in time for race day.

01:19.640 --> 01:21.140
I hope my van's here.

01:21.140 --> 01:22.480
[ clack ]
-that's a wrap.

01:22.480 --> 01:25.480
-- Captions by vitac --
 www.Vitac.Com

01:25.480 --> 01:28.480
captions paid for by
discovery communications

01:28.480 --> 01:32.350
♪

01:32.350 --> 01:34.690
richard: By now, y'all know
my style at gas monkey garage.

01:34.690 --> 01:36.190
We're always kicking down doors,

01:36.190 --> 01:38.730
throwing caution to the wind,
and you've seen it pay off

01:38.730 --> 01:40.260
with some incredible builds.

01:41.930 --> 01:44.430
There's the hi-po hauler build
from mattel's red line club.

01:44.430 --> 01:46.030
[ engine revs ]

01:46.040 --> 01:47.630
there's a super slick ford gt.

01:47.640 --> 01:52.240
No one's ever slammed
a gt on airbags before.

01:52.240 --> 01:54.070
And, of course,
the '34 ford coupe.

01:54.080 --> 01:56.740
Damn, it looks good. Hoo!
-Look at this thing, man.

01:56.750 --> 01:58.750
Now that's a hot rod.

01:58.750 --> 02:01.750
And we stepped down and built
a very big marketing truck

02:01.750 --> 02:05.290
for shiner beer, and it
turned out unbelievable,

02:05.290 --> 02:07.690
but the hard part
is keeping it going.

02:07.690 --> 02:10.260
I've gotta think outside
the box, do something different,

02:10.260 --> 02:11.830
push the envelope, if you will,

02:11.830 --> 02:13.290
and I think I got just
the thing to do it.

02:15.160 --> 02:17.200
[ horn honks ]

02:17.200 --> 02:18.300
ahoy, captain.

02:18.300 --> 02:19.470
It's a land yacht.

02:19.470 --> 02:20.630
-That is a land yacht.
-That is a yacht.

02:20.640 --> 02:22.140
That is the definition
of a land yacht.

02:22.140 --> 02:25.610
-Golly.
-Richard: '72 boattail.

02:25.610 --> 02:27.440
Check this out --
2-owner car,

02:27.440 --> 02:28.780
the guy had it
in his man cave.

02:28.780 --> 02:30.380
And I thought it was
pretty cool.

02:30.380 --> 02:32.650
I couldn't turn it down,
and it looked really nice.

02:32.650 --> 02:35.150
-They're kinda funky-looking.
-It's only got 40,000 miles?

02:35.150 --> 02:37.150
-That's what it's showing.
-Wow.

02:37.150 --> 02:38.390
Richard: We got
a wide open door there.

02:38.390 --> 02:39.820
Let's put it inside,
and we can talk about it.

02:39.820 --> 02:41.390
I didn't a/c this building
for the hell of it.

02:41.390 --> 02:42.660
-It's hot out here.
[ engine starts ]

02:42.660 --> 02:44.220
we can out everybody
on the hood of this thing.

02:44.230 --> 02:45.590
Slam on the breaks.

02:45.590 --> 02:46.730
[ tires screech ]

02:46.730 --> 02:47.960
-yeah, breaks work.
-[ laughs ]

02:47.960 --> 02:49.760
I survived. Don't worry.

02:51.230 --> 02:53.970
Richard: Holy cow! '72.

02:53.970 --> 02:55.870
Rad.

02:55.870 --> 02:57.910
Y'all remember I bought this
riviera out of a guy's man cave

02:57.910 --> 02:59.910
not that long ago
here in argyle, texas.

02:59.910 --> 03:01.240
I paid 10.5 for it.

03:01.240 --> 03:03.240
[ hood slams ]
listen to that.

03:03.250 --> 03:04.750
That was a steal
because it's got no rust,

03:04.750 --> 03:07.880
has never been wrecked,
and never been molested.

03:07.880 --> 03:09.720
I'm beginning to wonder
why you brought this car in

03:09.720 --> 03:11.990
to show us.
-I just think it's cool.

03:11.990 --> 03:13.590
-A riviera?
-It's a '72.

03:13.590 --> 03:15.460
Richard: Come on, man.
It's a boattail.

03:15.460 --> 03:17.260
What do you call that color?
Unattractive beige?

03:17.260 --> 03:18.530
-Buttermilk yellow.
[ hood pops ]

03:18.530 --> 03:19.690
-buttermilk yellow.
-Buttermilk yellow.

03:19.700 --> 03:21.090
Buttermilk yellow?

03:21.100 --> 03:23.200
We finally found a color
that's making me like green

03:23.200 --> 03:24.770
or black as an option.

03:24.770 --> 03:27.400
I've never seen a 455 motor
look so small in an engine bed.

03:27.400 --> 03:28.640
There's, like, a foot
back there.

03:28.640 --> 03:31.000
And back here, it's just
got such a sexy line.

03:31.010 --> 03:33.570
Brian: This reminds me of, like,
a '63 to '67 corvette.

03:33.580 --> 03:34.940
Yep.

03:34.940 --> 03:36.840
Same guy that designed
the corvette designed this car.

03:36.850 --> 03:38.710
-Richard: Did he?
-Yeah, yeah. Bill mitchell.

03:38.710 --> 03:40.150
Richard:
I got hot roder brian bass in

03:40.150 --> 03:42.250
because I've got something
really big planned,

03:42.250 --> 03:44.050
that'll make heads turn
and leave no doubt

03:44.050 --> 03:46.890
that gas monkey is the world's
number one hot rods shop.

03:48.220 --> 03:49.790
Brian's a top notch customizer
here in dallas,

03:49.790 --> 03:52.730
and really knocked it out
of the park on the '34 ford.

03:52.730 --> 03:54.230
Brian has the right eye
for design

03:54.230 --> 03:56.000
to make this build
really scream.

03:56.000 --> 03:57.460
Y'all, look at the car
for a second.

03:57.470 --> 03:59.200
I've done my job
and got it here.

03:59.200 --> 04:00.730
I want y'all to tell me
what I got for sure,

04:00.740 --> 04:04.000
because if I have what
I want, I got an idea.

04:04.010 --> 04:06.610
Buff it, fix the top,
and flip it.

04:06.610 --> 04:07.910
[ crack ]
-hey, hey, hey, hey, hey.

04:07.910 --> 04:09.110
-Whoa!
-You're already breaking stuff.

04:09.110 --> 04:10.910
[ clank ]

04:10.910 --> 04:13.280
sorry, yeah.

04:13.280 --> 04:16.420
Hey, hey, this is nice, not
having to push a car for once.

04:16.420 --> 04:17.580
Richard: I want the guys
to go over the car

04:17.590 --> 04:19.390
without me looking over
their shoulders.

04:19.390 --> 04:21.890
And if they confirm that
I got what I think I do,

04:21.890 --> 04:24.590
as far as a perfect canvas
to start with,

04:24.590 --> 04:26.690
we're golden,
because this is gonna be

04:26.700 --> 04:28.600
gas monkey's
first super car build

04:28.600 --> 04:30.600
unlike anything
anyone's ever seen,

04:30.600 --> 04:32.830
and I plan on taking it to sema.

04:32.840 --> 04:35.270
But when the guys find out
the crazy plan I've got in mind,

04:35.270 --> 04:37.240
they're gonna flip.

04:37.240 --> 04:38.810
Who already broke the top?

04:38.810 --> 04:39.940
-Josh broke it
-josh did it.

04:39.940 --> 04:42.910
-That idiot josh.
-Golly.

04:42.910 --> 04:44.340
Did I break it, or am I
making progress

04:44.350 --> 04:46.280
while you guys stand around?
-You're breaking it.

04:46.280 --> 04:47.980
[ laughing ]

04:47.980 --> 04:50.220
all right, so I think you could
just clean it up and sell it

04:50.220 --> 04:53.690
and get rid of the overspray
and maybe make some money.

04:53.690 --> 04:56.190
This thing's worth
12, 14 like it sits,

04:56.190 --> 04:57.860
and maybe 20 cleaned up.

04:57.860 --> 04:59.330
But then I got
to looking at it,

04:59.330 --> 05:02.900
and I'm like, I was looking
at the brand new zr1s

05:02.900 --> 05:05.700
that just came out,
and if you look at it

05:05.700 --> 05:08.240
in the right light
and squinting...

05:08.240 --> 05:09.440
[ laughs ]

05:09.440 --> 05:11.440
...This kinda looks like
an overgrown one.

05:11.440 --> 05:13.240
If you slammed this
and had it on the ground

05:13.240 --> 05:15.940
and slicked it up,
it can be sexy.

05:15.940 --> 05:17.640
Richard might have an eye
for car design,

05:17.650 --> 05:20.180
but "sexy" is not a word
I would use for this boat.

05:20.180 --> 05:22.450
This ain't no corvette.
This is, like, two corvettes.

05:22.450 --> 05:23.680
Imagine it down low.

05:23.690 --> 05:25.190
Imagine the wheels
and stance right.

05:25.190 --> 05:26.250
There's nothing
resembling a corvette

05:26.260 --> 05:27.690
on this car right now.

05:27.690 --> 05:28.990
Well, the back window does
look like a corvette.

05:28.990 --> 05:31.460
If you really look at it.
-You give us, what, three weeks?

05:31.460 --> 05:34.230
There's no way that we can
make this cool in three weeks.

05:34.230 --> 05:35.700
-What if I gave us months?

05:35.700 --> 05:37.160
[ speaks indistinctly ]
-you've never given us months.

05:37.170 --> 05:38.970
We've build hundreds of cars,
but no one's ever built

05:38.970 --> 05:41.440
quite what I have in my mind,
and if we get it right,

05:41.440 --> 05:43.100
people will be talking
about this car for years

05:43.110 --> 05:44.870
and that means they're
talking about gas monkey.

05:44.870 --> 05:46.040
But why?

05:47.180 --> 05:48.680
'cause I think it'd
be weird enough

05:48.680 --> 05:50.040
that people would freak out.

05:50.050 --> 05:52.250
The truck market is
hot right now.

05:52.250 --> 05:53.750
Why build a truck?

05:53.750 --> 05:54.750
This year at sema,
there's gonna be

05:54.750 --> 05:56.950
every one of those
every where.

05:56.950 --> 05:58.220
-Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.
-Wait a second.

05:58.220 --> 05:59.890
-What?
-Sema's...

05:59.890 --> 06:01.390
-Sema.
-Sema.

06:01.390 --> 06:02.660
Oh, man, I was hoping y'all
would come to that yourselves.

06:02.660 --> 06:03.820
[ laughter ]

06:03.830 --> 06:05.890
-there's the catch.
-There it is.

06:05.890 --> 06:07.130
Richard: That's right.

06:07.130 --> 06:09.400
I wanna build
a 1972 riviera for sema,

06:09.400 --> 06:11.470
the biggest automotive
trade show in the world.

06:11.470 --> 06:13.700
And the goal is to turn heads
and blow minds,

06:13.700 --> 06:15.770
in a way that only
gas monkey garage can.

06:15.770 --> 06:17.370
If we're doing a sema,
we can't do half-ass.

06:17.370 --> 06:18.640
We have to go all out.

06:18.640 --> 06:20.470
I want this thing
to be rippin' it.

06:20.480 --> 06:22.740
Really badass,
not a trailer queen.

06:22.750 --> 06:24.140
If it was up to me,
we'd drive it there.

06:24.150 --> 06:26.550
So this is gonna be our only
build for five months?

06:26.550 --> 06:27.810
Absolutely not.

06:27.820 --> 06:29.280
We still gotta stay open
and make money.

06:29.280 --> 06:30.450
We can clean it up and sell it
and make some money.

06:30.450 --> 06:32.220
We could go a little bit
further than that

06:32.220 --> 06:34.890
and make a really kick-ass car
that may or may not break out,

06:34.890 --> 06:39.060
or we can make a car that
make people go, "holy [bleep]."

06:39.060 --> 06:41.400
mike: It's not that we can't
make this riviera badass.

06:41.400 --> 06:44.030
That's not the problem.
Time's the problem.

06:44.030 --> 06:46.900
Make sure we got enough time
and especially enough budget.

06:46.900 --> 06:48.440
Jason:
You know, if you're building
a project in your garage

06:48.440 --> 06:50.440
and it goes south,
well, nobody has to know,

06:50.440 --> 06:52.540
but we put our necks
on the line every day here.

06:52.540 --> 06:53.940
If this one blows up on us,

06:53.940 --> 06:55.910
we're gonna look like
complete idiots.

06:55.910 --> 06:57.080
I love the ideas.

06:57.080 --> 06:58.450
I just -- the time window
I can see

06:58.450 --> 07:00.310
just getting shorter
and shorter.

07:00.320 --> 07:01.950
Richard: We're not gonna just
rest on our laurels.

07:01.950 --> 07:04.350
We have to take a risk
and spend our time

07:04.350 --> 07:06.550
over the next few months
building something

07:06.560 --> 07:08.090
that nobody's ever thought of.

07:08.090 --> 07:10.460
A build of this magnitude,
it really deserves a year,

07:10.460 --> 07:11.990
if not more.

07:11.990 --> 07:14.560
Getting it done in months and
putting it out there at sema?

07:14.560 --> 07:15.800
That's asking for trouble.

07:15.800 --> 07:18.060
This is all about upping
gas monkey as a brand.

07:18.070 --> 07:19.600
This is just
the next evolution.

07:19.600 --> 07:22.400
Let everybody know
that we're here to stay

07:22.400 --> 07:23.900
and we're
cutting [bleep] edge.

07:23.910 --> 07:25.070
-All right.
-Oh, yeah.

07:25.070 --> 07:26.710
So we're all in?
We're doing it?

07:26.710 --> 07:27.870
-I say we do it.
-I'm in.

07:27.880 --> 07:29.280
Hey, I like a challenge.

07:29.280 --> 07:30.440
We push all the time, we gotta
get up to that next level.

07:30.450 --> 07:31.610
Can we play with the color
a little bit?

07:31.610 --> 07:32.710
Mike:
Maybe not green, not black.

07:32.710 --> 07:34.350
Everybody's gonna
expect green out of us.

07:34.350 --> 07:36.650
Okay, I will give you my word,
we won't do green or black.

07:36.650 --> 07:38.650
Okay.

07:38.650 --> 07:40.220
Richard: This riviera build
is gonna be big.

07:40.220 --> 07:42.620
Sema's in five months, and that
sounds like a long way off,

07:42.620 --> 07:46.160
but it's not, not when
I'm putting 300k into a car.

07:46.160 --> 07:49.730
Yep, you heard that right.
This is a $300,000 build.

07:49.730 --> 07:50.930
I gotta
go draw something up.

07:50.930 --> 07:52.470
I mean, if we're gonna
do this thing,

07:52.470 --> 07:54.230
I need to have some kind
of design for us to go off of.

07:54.240 --> 07:55.640
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

07:55.640 --> 07:57.400
-That's a lot of fab work.
-I want big wheels, big lift.

07:57.410 --> 07:59.340
I want it tucked in there.

07:59.340 --> 08:02.280
I know what you like.
Let me go get started.

08:02.280 --> 08:04.710
Richard's idea is to bring
corvette cues into the riviera,

08:04.710 --> 08:07.250
and now I have to figure out
how to combine those two things,

08:07.250 --> 08:09.550
corvette and riviera,
and make it something

08:09.550 --> 08:12.490
that's practical
and possible to build.

08:12.490 --> 08:14.860
300k? That's a lot of money.
But five months?

08:14.860 --> 08:17.690
That's not really a lot of time
for a project that needs

08:17.690 --> 08:19.190
as much care and detail
as this one.

08:19.190 --> 08:21.600
Everyone has their doubts,
but when sema rolls around,

08:21.600 --> 08:23.030
one way or another,
we're gonna find out

08:23.030 --> 08:24.600
if richard bit off
more than we can chew.

08:24.600 --> 08:26.470
Five months is not
very long at all.

08:26.470 --> 08:27.970
But hey, we're gonna be
camping out a lot.

08:27.970 --> 08:29.500
Richard: I'll make us some
sleeping bags

08:29.510 --> 08:32.270
and hot dogs to roast.
-[ sighs heavily ]

08:32.270 --> 08:38.010
♪

08:38.010 --> 08:43.150
♪

08:43.150 --> 08:44.380
[ old timey horn honks ]

08:45.990 --> 08:46.990
goin' in?

08:46.990 --> 08:49.090
-It's coming in.
-All the way in.

08:49.090 --> 08:52.030
Daphne: Come on, before
richard gets here.

08:52.030 --> 08:53.290
I don't think we're gonna fit.

08:54.600 --> 08:55.900
We're not gonna let you
hit nothing.

08:55.900 --> 08:58.600
Richard: Whoa, whoa, whoa.
What are you numbskulls doing?

08:58.600 --> 09:00.100
Mike: I'm doing whatever
daphne's telling me to do,

09:00.100 --> 09:02.070
that's what I'm doin'.
-What is daphne saying?

09:02.070 --> 09:03.670
She wants the van inside.
[ engine idling ]

09:03.670 --> 09:04.870
I would do whatever
daphne said, too,

09:04.870 --> 09:06.470
except for
when I don't want to.

09:06.480 --> 09:08.710
In this case, no.

09:08.710 --> 09:11.850
There it is. Super cool.

09:11.850 --> 09:12.980
You better remember,

09:12.980 --> 09:14.650
I found this econoline van
in yuma, arizona.

09:14.650 --> 09:16.050
It didn't look like much,

09:16.050 --> 09:18.220
but what got my attention
was it's story.

09:18.220 --> 09:19.920
This is freakin' super cool.

09:19.920 --> 09:22.790
For 37 years, larry bisceglia
was the first in line

09:22.790 --> 09:24.560
to get into the indy 500.

09:24.560 --> 09:27.660
May 26th is larry bisceglia day.

09:27.660 --> 09:29.160
Ford finally gave
him a brand new van

09:29.160 --> 09:31.030
because imagine the years
of publicity.

09:31.030 --> 09:32.730
-5,500?
-We got a deal.

09:32.730 --> 09:34.830
Killer!
That's why I bought it,

09:34.840 --> 09:36.870
and just like ford did,
I see opportunity here.

09:38.670 --> 09:40.740
I'm giving this van away.
-To who?

09:40.740 --> 09:42.910
The indianapolis speedway
museum.

09:42.910 --> 09:44.780
For free.

09:44.780 --> 09:46.250
And here's the fun part --
you two guys are gonna drive it

09:46.250 --> 09:48.350
to indy, because it's gotta
be there on Friday.

09:48.350 --> 09:49.780
[ daphne laughs ]

09:49.790 --> 09:51.020
you're driving.

09:51.020 --> 09:53.290
If he can drive it from
scottsdale's phoenix area

09:53.290 --> 09:55.090
every year,
you can make it in one trip.

09:55.090 --> 09:57.190
So this hasn't ran
since the '80s...

09:57.190 --> 09:59.090
I drove it, like, two months ago
when we bought it.

09:59.090 --> 10:00.660
It barely pulled in the door.

10:00.660 --> 10:02.660
-I drove it around the block,
-it took an hour.

10:02.660 --> 10:04.730
-The engine sounds good.
-The block.

10:04.730 --> 10:06.400
Just throw it up in the air,
check everything front to back,

10:06.400 --> 10:08.570
and I can guarantee you,
this thing will make it.

10:08.570 --> 10:09.870
Get this thing back over there
and get ready to go to indy.

10:09.870 --> 10:12.170
Larry's van really does
belong in

10:12.170 --> 10:14.810
the indianapolis motor speedway
museum.

10:14.810 --> 10:16.540
I love that gas monkey can
play the part of returning it

10:16.550 --> 10:18.040
where it belongs.

10:18.050 --> 10:19.380
That's the fun in being
able to do the things we do,

10:19.380 --> 10:21.650
making a lasting mark
in the car community,

10:21.650 --> 10:24.250
and if I can get a little extra
media splash in the process,

10:24.250 --> 10:25.520
well, that's bonus points
for me.

10:25.520 --> 10:27.590
First go, not gonna
make it very far.

10:29.020 --> 10:30.260
We're gonna die.

10:31.760 --> 10:33.160
[ tires peal ]
-whoo!

10:33.160 --> 10:35.830
Narrator: Coming up
on "fast n' loud,"

10:35.830 --> 10:37.500
the riviera build
goes to pieces...

10:38.600 --> 10:39.770
[ laughing ]

10:39.770 --> 10:42.070
....And richard's secret life
revealed.

10:42.070 --> 10:44.140
You probably didn't even
know this, but I have a stepson.

10:44.140 --> 10:45.570
Get on in.

10:45.570 --> 10:47.140
-In this van?
-Yep.

10:47.140 --> 10:48.440
♪

10:48.440 --> 10:50.140
but there's not even
a seat for me!

10:56.420 --> 11:05.760
♪

11:05.760 --> 11:06.830
I think it's starting to
win me over a little bit.

11:06.830 --> 11:08.060
It does have some good lines.
-Yeah.

11:08.060 --> 11:09.430
I think
it's gonna be different,

11:09.430 --> 11:11.230
and I think that's what's
gonna be cool about it.

11:11.230 --> 11:12.500
There's not gonna be
five or six of these at sema.

11:12.500 --> 11:13.570
It's rare for a reason.

11:13.570 --> 11:14.770
Richard wants corvette elements

11:14.770 --> 11:16.040
and I think that we can do that

11:16.040 --> 11:17.570
without losing all
the buick riviera,

11:17.570 --> 11:18.870
and that's gonna
be the challenge,

11:18.870 --> 11:20.670
to bring these modern
corvette elements

11:20.680 --> 11:22.740
into this buick riviera.

11:22.740 --> 11:24.710
I do wanna have scoops,
a splitter on the front,

11:24.710 --> 11:26.180
and need a fuser on the rear.

11:26.180 --> 11:27.710
But the details can't
start to get worked out,

11:27.720 --> 11:29.250
until I finish up the sketch.

11:29.250 --> 11:30.880
We do know the body has
to go to the sand blaster,

11:30.890 --> 11:33.250
so there's no sense in waiting
to bust this thing down.

11:33.260 --> 11:35.960
The interior out, all the trim,
front, back bumpers,

11:35.960 --> 11:38.260
motor disconnected, so we
can lift the body off of it,

11:38.260 --> 11:39.560
and get this thing
outta the way.

11:39.560 --> 11:40.790
Let's get it apart.

11:42.330 --> 11:43.800
Brian: Pretty simple plan,
really.

11:43.800 --> 11:45.470
Jason and mike will focus
on the front and the motor...

11:45.470 --> 11:47.170
That's ingenious!

11:47.170 --> 11:49.970
...Tony and josh will focus
on the rear and the trim.

11:49.970 --> 11:51.240
Oh, my god, it's so heavy.

11:51.240 --> 11:52.940
...And jeremy and I will
pull out the interior.

11:52.940 --> 11:56.540
This car was built in '72 and
to make it a modern super car

11:56.550 --> 11:58.850
is not really gonna be
something that's easy.

11:58.850 --> 12:00.080
[ groans ]

12:00.080 --> 12:01.820
we have to change
the whole car, basically,

12:01.820 --> 12:05.620
and to do that with and keep
the same buick look and feel,

12:05.620 --> 12:07.790
and add corvette in the mix.

12:07.790 --> 12:08.990
I'm concerned about the fact

12:08.990 --> 12:10.720
that this is the size
of two corvettes.

12:10.730 --> 12:12.760
The corvette is
like half this car.

12:12.760 --> 12:16.230
[ whirring power-saw ]

12:16.230 --> 12:17.600
if we just go down
the wrong path and end up

12:17.600 --> 12:19.270
with something
that does not look good.

12:19.270 --> 12:20.630
It has to look the part.

12:20.640 --> 12:21.940
It has to act the part.

12:21.940 --> 12:23.170
It has to sound the part.

12:23.170 --> 12:24.340
Look, the part is
the most important, though,

12:24.340 --> 12:25.570
'cause that's my goal

12:25.570 --> 12:26.970
is to make it look as
good as I possibly can.

12:29.480 --> 12:30.980
And hopefully it'll smell
a lot better

12:30.980 --> 12:32.980
when I get done with it, too,
'cause it stinks right now.

12:32.980 --> 12:34.980
[ ripping ]

12:34.980 --> 12:36.020
oh, there we go.

12:36.020 --> 12:37.120
Aha.

12:37.120 --> 12:38.650
All right, bass,
making a mental note.

12:38.650 --> 12:39.850
You gotta remember how
that goes back together.

12:39.860 --> 12:40.950
I have no idea.

12:41.920 --> 12:44.220
[ clanking ]

12:45.490 --> 12:46.660
hey.

12:46.660 --> 12:48.160
Oh, grab the wire,
right here, watch this.

12:48.160 --> 12:50.630
[ clanking ]

12:50.630 --> 12:51.800
[ laughter ]

12:51.800 --> 12:54.070
all right, let's get
the body off.

12:54.070 --> 12:55.300
This thing got
so much lighter.

12:55.300 --> 12:56.470
It's all on the floor
over there.

12:56.470 --> 12:58.570
[ whirring ]
firewall's very heavy.

12:58.570 --> 13:00.770
Whoo-hoo-hoo.
I think we're home free.

13:00.780 --> 13:02.110
-Yeah.
-That is how it's done.

13:02.110 --> 13:05.310
Watch your fingers. Good?

13:05.310 --> 13:06.810
Let's get the gas tank out.

13:06.820 --> 13:09.450
[ drilling ]

13:09.450 --> 13:11.350
[ loud crash ]
-[ laughs ]

13:11.350 --> 13:12.490
whew!

13:12.490 --> 13:14.490
-That's one way of doing it.
-Yep.

13:14.490 --> 13:15.760
You know, there's that saying,

13:15.760 --> 13:16.990
'it's so crazy it
just might work'.

13:16.990 --> 13:19.190
Well, this build is like
'it's so effin' nuts,

13:19.190 --> 13:20.330
it better work'.

13:20.330 --> 13:21.760
No, it looks better already.

13:21.760 --> 13:23.400
The closer to the ground,
the better it looks.

13:23.400 --> 13:25.930
If we pull this off,
this car could become legend.

13:25.930 --> 13:27.270
It could be the car
the next generation

13:27.270 --> 13:28.640
of hot roders talk about.

13:28.640 --> 13:30.240
We went this far without
damaging anything,

13:30.240 --> 13:33.070
so it'd be a, you know, just
like us to drop it on the floor

13:33.070 --> 13:34.240
at this point.
[ laughter ]

13:34.240 --> 13:42.680
♪

13:42.680 --> 13:43.820
man: Speeding!

13:43.820 --> 13:51.930
♪

13:51.930 --> 13:55.090
all right. '72 rivi is back
from the sand blaster.

13:55.100 --> 13:56.360
-Hey, guys.
-Josh: No!

13:56.360 --> 13:59.100
Oh. My hands are clean.

14:00.970 --> 14:02.300
Well, mike, is it good?

14:02.300 --> 14:04.040
Yeah, it's super good.

14:04.040 --> 14:06.540
Super good. Whew! Man.

14:06.540 --> 14:08.980
Seems like we always waste
the best cars,

14:08.980 --> 14:10.280
the ones we cut up.

14:10.280 --> 14:11.910
Wait, wait, waste? Waste?
No, no, no, no, that's good.

14:11.910 --> 14:13.710
This means jeremy and I can
get straight to fabrication

14:13.720 --> 14:14.880
to do rust repair.

14:14.880 --> 14:16.050
That makes me happy.
-That is very true.

14:16.050 --> 14:17.180
Talk about good timing.

14:17.190 --> 14:18.350
I'm actually really
stoked on this because --

14:18.350 --> 14:19.590
oh, wow.

14:19.590 --> 14:21.050
You know, we talked
about this already

14:21.060 --> 14:22.560
and I think we kinda have
a good game plan now,

14:22.560 --> 14:23.820
and this is what I think it
should actually look like.

14:23.830 --> 14:25.190
Wow.

14:25.190 --> 14:26.760
Richard wants to
build a '72 riviera

14:26.760 --> 14:28.160
and present it at sema.

14:28.160 --> 14:29.630
It's gonna be
the most anticipated build

14:29.630 --> 14:30.900
gas monkey has ever done.

14:32.200 --> 14:33.770
I've been racking my brain,
talking to the guys,

14:33.770 --> 14:35.870
going over different styles,
different looks,

14:35.870 --> 14:37.640
and we finally came up with
a pretty good game plan

14:37.640 --> 14:40.740
for the riviera, and I just
finished the rendering for it

14:40.740 --> 14:41.910
when it came back
from sand blasting,

14:41.910 --> 14:43.740
so really good timing.

14:43.750 --> 14:46.810
Carbon fiber hood, bronze
wheels with a polished lip

14:46.820 --> 14:48.650
and polished knock-offs.
-Yep.

14:48.650 --> 14:50.820
I wanna do the split bumpers
like a '70 model camaro.

14:50.820 --> 14:52.990
Yeah, so that looks like
it's got the chop top.

14:52.990 --> 14:54.220
It does have a chop top.

14:54.220 --> 14:55.720
I'm thinking, like, an inch,
inch and a half

14:55.720 --> 14:58.020
of the front only, so we'll
take all that wedge shape

14:58.030 --> 14:59.530
out of it and bring it down...
-Yeah.

14:59.530 --> 15:01.260
...Make it a little bit meaner,
little more aggressive.

15:01.260 --> 15:03.230
You know, all these
really cool details

15:03.230 --> 15:04.960
will make this thing

15:04.970 --> 15:07.730
more of a modern
pro-touring luxury car.

15:07.740 --> 15:09.440
All these things, you know,
we're just talking about

15:09.440 --> 15:11.040
things that are
really time consuming,

15:11.040 --> 15:12.940
and we're really
already under the gun.

15:12.940 --> 15:14.810
This car has, like, these
natural hips right here

15:14.810 --> 15:16.340
and I think we should
accentuate that.

15:16.340 --> 15:17.780
And, you know,
one of richard's ideas

15:17.780 --> 15:20.310
was to take the corvette cues
and bring them into the riviera,

15:20.320 --> 15:22.450
so I was thinking a vent there
for a break vent,

15:22.450 --> 15:23.720
I think that's
a really cool idea.

15:23.720 --> 15:25.290
It'll naturally fit there.

15:25.290 --> 15:27.190
I came up with a name
for the car.

15:27.190 --> 15:28.420
Uh-oh.

15:28.420 --> 15:29.660
I wanna call it
the battleship buick,

15:29.660 --> 15:30.920
because it's gonna be
battleship gray

15:30.930 --> 15:32.360
and it's a mean boattail car.
-I don't hate it.

15:32.360 --> 15:33.660
I don't hate it.
-I don't hate that at all

15:33.660 --> 15:36.200
brian: This car being
a boattail buick riviera,

15:36.200 --> 15:37.660
it's a big ol' boat,
it's a land yacht,

15:37.670 --> 15:39.630
but we're making it
into a performance car.

15:39.630 --> 15:41.570
That makes it a
battleship in my eyes.

15:41.570 --> 15:43.670
Somebody needs to talk about
the elephant in the room,

15:43.670 --> 15:45.770
and I'm not talking
about jeremy.

15:45.770 --> 15:46.770
Damn.
What else is it?

15:46.780 --> 15:48.410
What is it?
Time.

15:48.410 --> 15:51.440
Five months, but we
have other projects

15:51.450 --> 15:53.180
in that time, too.

15:53.180 --> 15:54.850
Technically we're probably
only really getting,

15:54.850 --> 15:57.480
what, two months, three, maybe?

15:57.490 --> 15:59.550
I think this might be one of
the most fab heavy projects

15:59.550 --> 16:00.850
that gas monkey has ever done,

16:00.860 --> 16:02.290
and we're gonna
be under the gun,

16:02.290 --> 16:03.290
and we have to work
together to get this done.

16:03.290 --> 16:04.490
Every one of us has to chip in

16:04.490 --> 16:06.090
and get the fabrication
side of this thing.

16:06.090 --> 16:07.530
What do you think
you need time wise

16:07.530 --> 16:08.760
as far as body?

16:08.760 --> 16:09.960
This body's pretty straight.

16:09.970 --> 16:11.660
There'll be heavy mods,
but as far as --

16:11.670 --> 16:12.970
three weeks,
give me three weeks.

16:12.970 --> 16:14.300
Three weeks? Have you ever
had three weeks

16:14.300 --> 16:16.100
to paint a car before?
-No, that's what I'm saying.

16:16.100 --> 16:17.470
Have y'all ever had five months
to do metal work?

16:17.470 --> 16:19.240
-No.
-All right, three weeks.

16:19.240 --> 16:20.970
We're breaking new ground here.

16:20.980 --> 16:22.140
-Give me three weeks.
-All right, three weeks.

16:22.140 --> 16:24.080
I've built a couple
sema cars before,

16:24.080 --> 16:25.550
and there's definitely a crunch,

16:25.550 --> 16:29.150
but five months from the get-go,
from coming up with an idea?

16:29.150 --> 16:31.150
I know these guys work fast,
but it's gonna be a tight --

16:31.150 --> 16:32.420
a tight squeeze.

16:32.420 --> 16:33.590
What are we looking
at power point-wise?

16:33.590 --> 16:36.290
Super charged, lt-4, chevy.

16:36.290 --> 16:39.060
1,000, 1,200 horse power
is what I'm hearing.

16:39.060 --> 16:40.230
-[ laughs ]
-lotta gear.

16:40.230 --> 16:41.490
Yeah, that's awesome.

16:41.500 --> 16:42.660
All that horse power means
that the original chassis

16:42.660 --> 16:43.860
is headed for the scrap pile.

16:43.870 --> 16:45.330
We'll need a new chassis,

16:45.330 --> 16:47.930
a custom one that's not only
stronger, but lighter,

16:47.940 --> 16:49.200
and specifically designed,

16:49.200 --> 16:51.500
so we can mount
the independent suspension.

16:51.510 --> 16:52.970
This is gonna be
a super expensive build.

16:52.970 --> 16:54.810
This is gonna be
the most expensive build

16:54.810 --> 16:56.040
we've ever built
at gas monkey.

16:56.040 --> 16:57.580
And our most ambitious build.

16:57.580 --> 16:59.680
Not only is this just
gonna take a lot of time,

16:59.680 --> 17:01.050
it's also gonna
take a lot of money.

17:01.050 --> 17:02.550
Richard seems to be
okay with it right now,

17:02.550 --> 17:05.050
but I can foresee four,
five months down the line,

17:05.050 --> 17:06.520
richard may not be quite as okay

17:06.520 --> 17:08.120
with how much money we're
spending on this car.

17:08.120 --> 17:10.520
I actually saw some moths
fly out of richard's wallet,

17:10.530 --> 17:11.720
like he's getting into parts

17:11.730 --> 17:12.730
he's never actually
got into before.

17:12.730 --> 17:13.960
[ laughs ] yeah.

17:13.960 --> 17:15.460
The biggest issue
is that the chassis

17:15.460 --> 17:16.900
has to be built first,
and that's gonna take some time.

17:16.900 --> 17:19.300
So in the meantime, I tackle
all the heavy body mods,

17:19.300 --> 17:20.830
and then really,
when the chassis comes in,

17:20.840 --> 17:23.100
we'll be ready to set the body
on it and go to town.

17:23.100 --> 17:27.040
[ laughing ]
-let's go to work.

17:27.040 --> 17:28.210
I gotta go wash my hands.

17:28.210 --> 17:30.540
♪

17:30.550 --> 17:32.780
-tony: I think that's it.
