on the doors,

31:42.260 --> 31:44.430
what was making me see it weird.

31:44.430 --> 31:46.500
Now that it...
Everything goes.

31:46.500 --> 31:48.570
-I think the top's spot on.
-I like the top.

31:48.570 --> 31:50.000
Josh: I'd like to see
the hood's gonna bring

31:50.000 --> 31:51.470
the front up, too, so it's
gonna look even more chopped.

31:51.470 --> 31:53.240
I like it.
I like where we're headin'.

31:53.240 --> 31:54.410
Let's stick it together.

31:54.410 --> 32:00.310
♪

32:00.310 --> 32:02.880
just taking a little bit
of material out of the top

32:02.880 --> 32:05.020
made it a much more
aggressive car.

32:05.020 --> 32:06.590
I'm-a stick it.
-Yeah.

32:06.590 --> 32:07.820
Brian: And I would
normally wanna cut a car

32:07.820 --> 32:09.760
a little more than this,
but cutting it an inch

32:09.760 --> 32:11.760
worked out to be
just the right amount.

32:13.390 --> 32:16.060
-Did we already lay it down?
-Yeah. You can't tell?

32:16.060 --> 32:18.260
What do you think?
-That's rad!

32:18.270 --> 32:19.830
Brian: It's down
a full inch in the front.

32:19.830 --> 32:21.200
It's what we decided on.

32:21.200 --> 32:22.500
If you measure it from
the window line, it's actually,

32:22.500 --> 32:24.400
like, an eighth inch lower
in the front now.

32:24.410 --> 32:25.840
Before it was, like, what?
A full...

32:25.840 --> 32:27.540
-Inch.
-Solid inch.

32:27.540 --> 32:30.380
Brian: It's not a drastic chop
like we would normally think of

32:30.380 --> 32:31.880
when we say chop a top,

32:31.880 --> 32:34.980
but we did this in the most
efficient manner possible.

32:34.980 --> 32:36.620
I looked up and you guys
already had it done.

32:36.620 --> 32:37.850
I don't think you could
chop a car like this

32:37.850 --> 32:39.120
any faster than we did it.

32:39.120 --> 32:40.720
That's slick. I like it.

32:40.720 --> 32:42.020
Brian: When richard and I
first started talking

32:42.020 --> 32:44.160
about the design for this car,

32:44.160 --> 32:46.220
he wanted to chop the top, and I
was a little unsure of that

32:46.230 --> 32:47.430
because I didn't think
we could do it

32:47.430 --> 32:48.560
in the time frame that we had.

32:48.560 --> 32:50.330
We got it done,
but I still have my doubts

32:50.330 --> 32:51.730
about making it to sema.

32:51.730 --> 32:53.570
Time is really against us
on this one.

32:53.570 --> 32:54.830
Richard: Y'all keep going,
'cause this is the biggest

32:54.840 --> 32:56.670
bite of the apple
we've taken so far.

32:56.670 --> 32:58.270
I'm on my way to indy.

32:58.270 --> 33:00.410
Hopefully the boys in the van
made it.

33:00.410 --> 33:04.810
♪

33:04.810 --> 33:08.350
announcer:<i> Please have your</i>
<i> tickets out and ready...</i>

33:08.350 --> 33:09.510
I just got to

33:09.520 --> 33:11.050
the indianapolis
motor speedway museum.

33:11.050 --> 33:12.920
The guys should be here
with the van any minute now,

33:12.920 --> 33:14.850
so I've got a little time
to check out a couple of cars

33:14.860 --> 33:16.090
with the curator, jason.

33:16.090 --> 33:18.460
We have a pretty
fabulous collection here

33:18.460 --> 33:19.930
of race cars, pace cars.

33:19.930 --> 33:22.290
I'm jason vansickle.
I'm the curator at

33:22.300 --> 33:24.400
the indianapolis motor speedway
museum.

33:24.400 --> 33:25.700
This thing is rad.

33:25.700 --> 33:28.270
Yeah, that's a 1911
indianapolis 500 winner,

33:28.270 --> 33:30.170
the first indianapolis
500 winner.

33:30.170 --> 33:32.540
It was a little radical
because it was a single-seater

33:32.540 --> 33:34.440
compared to the 2-man
cars of the era.

33:34.440 --> 33:36.480
70, 80 miles an hour?

33:36.480 --> 33:38.940
Yeah, it averaged at
just under 75 miles an hour.

33:38.950 --> 33:46.650
♪

33:46.650 --> 33:48.350
I hope my van's here.

33:51.130 --> 33:53.490
-Hey, we're almost here, fellas.
-Sinjin: I guess so.

33:53.490 --> 33:56.530
Now remember, we see richard,
we didn't stop anywhere.

33:56.530 --> 33:57.760
We drove straight through.

33:57.770 --> 33:59.260
Uh-huh, non-stop.
We just stopped for fuel.

33:59.270 --> 34:01.830
♪

34:01.840 --> 34:03.200
mike: Whoo-hoo!

34:03.200 --> 34:04.940
I think we may be
the first ones here, boys.

34:04.940 --> 34:07.040
[ old timey horn honking ]

34:07.040 --> 34:09.570
mike: Richard had tony and me
drive the "first in line" van

34:09.580 --> 34:11.340
all the way to indianapolis,

34:11.350 --> 34:14.310
<i> and</i> he made us take his
social media millennial stepson

34:14.310 --> 34:16.310
along for the 900-mile ride.
Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

34:16.320 --> 34:17.820
Sinjin: I'm ready
to get outta this van.

34:17.820 --> 34:20.420
I think I might just get out
and kiss the ground right now.

34:20.420 --> 34:23.760
Three days with daddy's boy,
and I still don't trust him.

34:23.760 --> 34:25.090
Me neither.

34:25.090 --> 34:27.630
Mike: And like we said earlier,
we didn't stop anywhere,

34:27.630 --> 34:28.660
we drove straight through.

34:28.660 --> 34:30.030
Look at that!

34:30.030 --> 34:31.300
[ old timey horn honks ]

34:31.300 --> 34:32.630
they made it.

34:32.630 --> 34:35.500
If you give three knuckleheads
a freakin' chore,

34:35.500 --> 34:37.900
one of 'em
will make it happen.

34:37.910 --> 34:40.170
Yes!

34:40.170 --> 34:43.310
Look at that!
-Did you get your job done?

34:43.310 --> 34:45.410
-I-I got it done.
-Look at this.

34:45.410 --> 34:48.150
Jason: Richard purchased
the 1967 ford econoline van

34:48.150 --> 34:50.320
about a year ago
and has donated it here

34:50.320 --> 34:52.550
to the indianapolis
motor speedway museum.

34:52.550 --> 34:55.090
-I think it belongs here.
-Yeah.

34:55.090 --> 34:56.620
We wanted to purchase it
about a year ago,

34:56.620 --> 34:59.160
but bein' a not for profit,
it's hard to acquire cars.

34:59.160 --> 35:02.190
So when richard showed up
wantin' to donate it,

35:02.200 --> 35:03.700
it was a blessing.

35:03.700 --> 35:06.830
Bisceglia was a folk hero,
and a lot of the fans remember

35:06.830 --> 35:08.270
this van in the infield.

35:08.270 --> 35:09.940
He was a legend,
and that's great.

35:09.940 --> 35:12.770
-Where'd you get the cowboy hat?
-Convenience store.

35:12.770 --> 35:14.240
We stopped for gas.
-Tony: Yep.

35:14.240 --> 35:15.970
-Sinjin: And we stopped --
mike: Hey.

35:15.980 --> 35:17.810
Sinjin: It was good, made it
all the way through

35:17.810 --> 35:18.840
and didn't make any pit stops.

35:18.850 --> 35:20.050
Yeah, just for fuel.

35:20.050 --> 35:21.350
Really, you just
rolled right in?

35:21.350 --> 35:23.450
Part of the team now.
He's part of the team.

35:23.450 --> 35:25.820
-Not a problem?
-No problems at all.

35:25.820 --> 35:27.020
Richard:
Now that larry's van is here,

35:27.020 --> 35:28.090
the gas monkey name
will be part of

35:28.090 --> 35:29.990
the indy 500 history forever.

35:29.990 --> 35:32.990
Man, I gotta tell ya,
that's priceless.

35:32.990 --> 35:34.660
-I need a beer.
-Wait, hold on.

35:34.660 --> 35:35.890
What?

35:35.900 --> 35:37.060
One last selfie
to end this trip.

35:37.060 --> 35:38.230
Mike: Come on, get it done.

35:38.230 --> 35:40.400
[ camera shutter clicks ]

35:40.400 --> 35:42.130
sinjin: First beer
is on richard?

35:42.140 --> 35:43.600
Mike: This has been
a great trip, honestly.

35:43.600 --> 35:46.670
I mean, it was hot
and it was tiring,

35:46.670 --> 35:51.640
but the reward to just bring it
here and have it back home...

35:51.650 --> 35:52.810
It's time to party.

35:52.810 --> 35:53.810
I feel like drivin' it
back home.

35:53.810 --> 35:55.250
Sinjin: No, no, let's not.

35:55.250 --> 35:57.580
[ old timey horn honks ]

35:57.580 --> 35:59.420
[ engine revs, tires peal ]
-richard: Whoo!

35:59.420 --> 36:01.550
Narrator:
Comin' up on "fast n' loud,"

36:01.560 --> 36:05.190
the monkeys rock the riviera
heavy metal..

36:05.190 --> 36:06.360
♪ yeah! ♪

36:06.360 --> 36:07.590
making good progress.

36:07.590 --> 36:10.230
...But richard is singing
a sema swan song.

36:10.230 --> 36:12.500
The progress does look good,
but we got a problem.

36:12.500 --> 36:13.800
Give us the bad news.

36:13.800 --> 36:16.030
♪

36:22.340 --> 36:23.510
[ siren wailing ]

36:23.510 --> 36:24.940
-sinjin: Hey, uh, mike?
-Mike: Yeah?

36:24.950 --> 36:27.250
Uh...

36:27.250 --> 36:30.050
All right, mr. Koi is it?
Like the fish?

36:30.050 --> 36:31.520
Yes, but it's spelled
different, yeah.

36:31.520 --> 36:32.680
Officer: But it's spelled
different, okay.

36:32.690 --> 36:34.090
Where are you guys
goin' with this car?

36:34.090 --> 36:36.490
Sir, we're goin' to indy,
the indy 500.

36:36.490 --> 36:38.620
-You're gonna race in this?
-No, we're not gonna race in it.

36:38.630 --> 36:40.860
What's he sitting on?
Is that a seat?

36:40.860 --> 36:42.560
It is a seat shaped like cooler.

36:42.560 --> 36:43.860
All right, sir, here's what's
gonna happen, all right.

36:43.860 --> 36:45.030
I'm gonna cut you loose
with a warning.

36:45.030 --> 36:46.430
Is a selfie out of the question?

36:46.430 --> 36:48.070
If you want a selfie,
that'll be fine, sir.

36:48.070 --> 36:49.270
-Really?
-Ha.

36:49.270 --> 36:51.670
[ camera shutter clicks ]
-officer: Say, "license."

36:57.950 --> 37:06.150
♪

37:06.150 --> 37:07.850
brian: Right now we're filling
what's called the marker lights

37:07.850 --> 37:09.090
on the side of the car.

37:09.090 --> 37:10.420
We're gonna fill all
the factory trim holes,

37:10.420 --> 37:12.120
so this car's gonna be
a lot slicker than it was

37:12.130 --> 37:13.560
when it left the factory.

37:13.560 --> 37:16.660
'72 buick riviera's already
a pretty slick car,

37:16.660 --> 37:19.260
but just these removal
of these few little barbs

37:19.270 --> 37:21.030
really makes it look
a lot more sleek,

37:21.030 --> 37:22.230
a lot more aggressive.

37:22.240 --> 37:24.100
Which is obviously
what we're going for.

37:24.100 --> 37:26.910
♪

37:26.910 --> 37:28.370
jeremy: With the new chassis
that's coming,

37:28.380 --> 37:30.640
we'll have to ditch
the entire floor,

37:30.640 --> 37:32.880
rear fender wells,
trunk, everything.

37:32.880 --> 37:34.910
I mean, just an outside shell
and a roof

37:34.920 --> 37:36.310
is all that'll be left.

37:36.320 --> 37:37.750
We got some big, old tires

37:37.750 --> 37:40.850
and really cool suspension
going in the back of this thing.

37:40.850 --> 37:42.420
We'd like to cut
this all out now.

37:42.420 --> 37:48.190
♪

37:48.200 --> 37:53.970
♪

37:53.970 --> 37:55.300
dude, I'm totally floored.

37:55.300 --> 37:59.000
[ forced laughter ]
stupid.

37:59.010 --> 38:01.770
With the trunk floor deleted
and still more to cut out,

38:01.780 --> 38:04.110
we're gonna need a lot
of bracing inside.

38:04.110 --> 38:06.380
Can you grab your stinger
and zappy zappy?

38:06.380 --> 38:08.180
[ crackling ]
got 'em one by one.

38:08.180 --> 38:10.750
In the end, that's what's gonna
keep this car right and nice.

38:10.750 --> 38:16.350
♪

38:16.360 --> 38:18.160
now that the trunk
is all braced up,

38:18.160 --> 38:19.760
I can get cutting on
the inner wheel wells.

38:19.760 --> 38:21.160
Guess I gotta get in here
and get to cuttin'.

38:21.160 --> 38:22.330
Chop chop.

38:22.330 --> 38:29.330
♪

38:29.340 --> 38:30.940
jeremy: Even though
we don't got a chassis,

38:30.940 --> 38:32.140
we know there's a lot of metal

38:32.140 --> 38:34.310
that's still gonna be
in the way.

38:34.310 --> 38:39.440
♪

38:39.450 --> 38:44.580
♪

38:44.580 --> 38:46.080
brian: There's nothing precise
about sticking the tire

38:46.090 --> 38:47.920
in the wheel well,
but at least we get an idea

38:47.920 --> 38:49.590
of how it's gonna look.

38:49.590 --> 38:51.320
And if this mock-up
is any indication,

38:51.330 --> 38:52.990
it's gonna be badass.

38:52.990 --> 38:55.290
That's about right height
right there.

38:55.300 --> 38:56.590
Tucked in the lip.

38:56.600 --> 38:59.330
-[ sighs ] okay.
-Excited?

38:59.330 --> 39:00.970
It looks good, though.
It really does.

39:00.970 --> 39:02.330
I think it looks good.

39:02.340 --> 39:03.640
Brian: But now we've done
just about everything we can

39:03.640 --> 39:05.070
until the chassis gets here.

39:05.070 --> 39:07.510
Sema may seem like months away,
but that clock is ticking.

39:07.510 --> 39:09.370
We got tons of work
left ahead of us.

39:10.340 --> 39:12.310
That's a whole lotta tire.

39:12.310 --> 39:13.980
But it's a whole lotta car, too.

39:13.980 --> 39:17.080
♪

39:17.080 --> 39:18.880
richard: When we got rolling
on the '72 riviera,

39:18.890 --> 39:20.520
I wasn't kidding when
I said it was gonna be

39:20.520 --> 39:22.250
a superbuild
worth taking to sema,

39:22.260 --> 39:24.660
and that's gonna take time
<i> and</i> money.

39:24.660 --> 39:27.460
Now $300,000?
That is a lot of money.

39:27.460 --> 39:30.130
But five months ain't a lot of
time, not for this car build.

39:30.130 --> 39:31.700
Why is everybody
standin' around?

39:31.700 --> 39:33.730
Well, we're talkin'
about the next step.

39:33.730 --> 39:35.170
Makin' good progress.

39:35.170 --> 39:36.870
Progress does look good,
but we got a problem.

39:36.870 --> 39:39.370
Chris alston chassisworks
just called, and we gave 'em

39:39.370 --> 39:40.940
a tall order -- I knew it
when we went in --

39:40.940 --> 39:43.410
and it's
a little bit delayed.

39:43.410 --> 39:44.680
Delayed?

39:44.680 --> 39:46.040
It's a little bit, like,
not delayed.

39:46.050 --> 39:47.210
We're supposed to be getting it
like next week, right?

39:47.210 --> 39:48.550
Not comin' and it's not
their fault.

39:48.550 --> 39:50.720
Give us the bad news.
How late is it gonna be?

39:50.720 --> 39:51.920
Two weeks.

39:51.920 --> 39:54.020
-Later? Later?
-So a month.

39:54.020 --> 39:55.490
A month from right now?

39:55.490 --> 39:56.720
Yeah, this isn't somethin' that
was sittin' in the computer

39:56.720 --> 39:57.990
they could punch out.

39:57.990 --> 40:00.020
Last year we had
two amazing vehicles at sema,

40:00.030 --> 40:01.290
and that was a huge deal.

40:01.290 --> 40:02.930
I mean, it was
a lot of pride.

40:02.930 --> 40:05.160
Everybody seemed to
really love what we did,

40:05.170 --> 40:06.560
and this is taking it
to the next step.

40:06.570 --> 40:07.930
We have to be at sema.

40:07.930 --> 40:09.200
Yeah, that's where
this car has to be.

40:09.200 --> 40:10.440
Do they have any part of it?

40:10.440 --> 40:11.900
Do they have
a rear end assembly?

40:11.910 --> 40:13.440
I kinda went down that
rabbit trail with him,

40:13.440 --> 40:15.810
but the problem is, is if
you remember the old thing

40:15.810 --> 40:17.480
where they started in the east
and started in the west

40:17.480 --> 40:18.740
and built the railroads
and missed.

40:18.750 --> 40:20.810
I don't wanna do that
from front to back.

40:20.810 --> 40:22.050
Brian: We made as much
progress as we can

40:22.050 --> 40:23.550
without having the chassis.

40:23.550 --> 40:25.150
We can't fabricate parts now
without having foundation

40:25.150 --> 40:26.680
of the build.

40:26.690 --> 40:28.190
Richard said we'd be workin'
other cars at the same time,

40:28.190 --> 40:30.320
but that time came a
little sooner than I hoped.

40:30.320 --> 40:31.790
It would be a huge
disappointment

40:31.790 --> 40:33.630
if we didn't have this car
there, at least if not for us

40:33.630 --> 40:35.130
but for our manufacturers
that are helping us

40:35.130 --> 40:36.290
with this project.

40:36.300 --> 40:37.760
Well, I told him,
we're aiming for sema

40:37.760 --> 40:40.170
but it's a production,
it's a vehicle,

40:40.170 --> 40:42.370
and if we make it,
we make it.

40:42.370 --> 40:43.800
People wanna see this thing,
I think, ya know?

40:43.800 --> 40:45.140
People are talkin'
about it on the net.

40:45.140 --> 40:46.600
-Right.
-They know we're buildin' it.

40:46.610 --> 40:48.240
They're wonderin' what
we're doin' with a '72 riviera,

40:48.240 --> 40:49.510
but the talk's there.

40:49.510 --> 40:51.210
The countdown clock to sema
is ticking,

40:51.210 --> 40:52.710
but we don't have a choice.

40:52.710 --> 40:54.650
We've got to set the riviera
aside and wait for parts.

40:54.650 --> 40:55.850
Sorry for the bad news.

40:55.850 --> 40:57.980
Just push all the [bleep]
together and...

40:57.980 --> 40:59.450
Let's do something else.

40:59.450 --> 41:02.490
What a buzzkill, dude.
I was having a good time.

41:02.490 --> 41:03.790
Well, there you go.

41:03.790 --> 41:06.660
So tryin' to get to sema
and, you know, things happen.

41:06.660 --> 41:08.130
Those guys are tryin' to
get to sema, too,

41:08.130 --> 41:11.000
so everybody's on board,
nobody's doin' anything wrong,

41:11.000 --> 41:13.600
we just time and money,
time and money.

41:13.600 --> 41:19.300
♪

41:19.310 --> 41:21.110
-let's knock it out.
-Narrator: Still ahead

41:21.110 --> 41:24.040
on this season on
"fast n' loud,"

41:24.040 --> 41:26.380
even as richard brings in
fresh projects,

41:26.380 --> 41:29.310
the clock is ticking down
on the riviera's "superbuild."

41:29.320 --> 41:30.920
how long until the frame's
put together?

41:30.920 --> 41:32.780
Narrator: The monkeys will face
new challenges

41:32.790 --> 41:36.490
on their biggest, baddest,
most expensive build ever.

41:36.490 --> 41:38.260
You'll just have to bring
a wheelbarrow full of hundreds.

41:38.260 --> 41:39.720
A wheelbarrow.

41:39.730 --> 41:43.090
Narrator: Catch every episode
to follow the buick riviera...

41:43.100 --> 41:44.330
We're goin' to katech.

41:44.330 --> 41:47.000
...As it's transformed
from giant land yacht...

41:47.000 --> 41:48.230
Check it out, richard.

41:48.240 --> 41:49.470
Super rad!

41:49.470 --> 41:51.240
...Into the ultimate
gentleman's hot rod.

41:51.240 --> 41:52.900
There's a lot more riding
on this riviera build

41:52.910 --> 41:54.370
than the 300k that
I'm puttin' into it.

41:54.370 --> 41:55.870
Did I just say "300k"?

41:55.880 --> 41:57.040
♪

41:57.040 --> 41:58.280
[ clack ]
